{"title_page": "Immigration to Costa Rica", "text_new": "As of the 2011 census, the number of '''immigrants in Costa Rica''' totaled about 390,000 individuals, or about 9% of the country's population.<ref name=inmigranteinec>{{cite web|title=Costa Rica: Poblaci\u00f3n total nacida en el extranjero por zona y sexo, seg\u00fan pa\u00eds de nacimiento y a\u00f1o de llegada al pa\u00eds|url=http://www.inec.go.cr/sites/default/files/documentos/poblacion/migracion/estadisticas/resultados/repoblaccenso2011-03.xls.xls|website=Instituto Nacional de Estad\u00edstica y Censos|accessdate=27 December 2017|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Costa Rica: Poblaci\u00f3n total por lugar de nacimiento, seg\u00fan provincia de residencia actual y sexo|url=http://www.inec.go.cr/sites/default/files/documentos/poblacion/estadisticas/resultados/repoblaccenso2011-04.xls.xls|website=Instituto Nacional de Estad\u00edstica y Censos|accessdate=27 December 2017|language=Spanish}}</ref> Following a considerable drop from 1950 through 1980, immigration to [[Costa Rica]] has increased in recent decades.\n\nThe ethnic composition of Costa Rica consists mostly of people of [[European Costa Rican|European]] origin, with a large population of [[Mestizos]] and numerically fewer [[Afro-Costa Rican|black]] and [[Indigenous peoples of Costa Rica|indigenous]] people.\n\n{| class=\"toc\" cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=20% style=\"float:right; text-align:left;clear:all; margin-left:20px; font-size:90%;\"\n!bgcolor=black colspan=8 style=\"color:white;\"|total foreign population 2012<ref name=inmigranteinec/>\n|- bgcolor=\"#efefef\"\n!Place.\n!Country.\n!Numbers.\n|-\n|1||{{flag2|Nicaragua}}|| align=\"right\" |287&nbsp;766\n|-\n|2||{{flag2|Colombia}}|| align=\"right\" |16&nbsp;514\n|-\n|3||{{flag2|United States}}|| align=\"right\" |15&nbsp;898\n|-\n|4||{{flag2|Panama}}|| align=\"right\" |11&nbsp;250\n|-\n|5||{{flag2|El Salvador}}|| align=\"right\" |9&nbsp;424\n|-\n|6||{{flag2|Venezuela}}|| align=\"right\" |&nbsp;3 886\n|-\n|7||{{flag2|Cuba}}|| align=\"right\" |3&nbsp;860\n|-\n|8||{{flag2|Honduras}}|| align=\"right\" |3&nbsp;778\n|-\n|9||{{flag2|Peru}}|| align=\"right\" |3&nbsp;404\n|-\n|10||{{flag2|China}}|| align=\"right\" |3&nbsp;281\n|-\n|11||{{flag2|Mexico}}|| align=\"right\" |3&nbsp;059\n|-\n|12||{{flag2|Guatemala}}|| align=\"right\" | 2 573\n|-\n|13||{{flag2|Spain}}|| align=\"right\" |&nbsp;1 806\n|-\n|14||{{flag2|Argentina}}|| align=\"right\" |1&nbsp;786\n|-\n|15||{{flag2|Canada}}|| align=\"right\" |&nbsp;1 679\n|-\n|16||{{flag2|Italy}}|| align=\"right\" |1&nbsp;494\n|-\n|17||{{flag2|Dominican Republic}}|| align=\"right\" |1&nbsp;475\n|-\n|18||{{flag2|Germany}}|| align=\"right\" |1&nbsp;412\n|-\n|19||{{flag2|Chile}}|| align=\"right\" |1&nbsp;364\n|-\n|20||{{flag2|Ecuador}}|| align=\"right\" |1&nbsp;040\n|-\n|21||{{flag2|France}}|| align=\"right\" |936\n|-\n|22||{{flag2|Taiwan}}|| align=\"right\" |797\n|-\n|23||{{flag2|Brazil}}|| align=\"right\" |605\n|-\n|24||{{flag2|Switzerland}}|| align=\"right\" |551\n|-\n|25||{{flag2|England}}|| align=\"right\" |503\n|-\n|26||{{flag2|Netherlands}}|| align=\"right\" |434\n|-\n|27||{{flag2|Russia}}|| align=\"right\" |429\n|-\n|28||{{flag2|Uruguay}}|| align=\"right\" |356\n|-\n|29||{{flag2|Bolivia}}|| align=\"right\" |331\n|-\n|30||{{flag2|South Korea}}|| align=\"right\" |263\n|-\n|31||{{flag2|Belgium}}|| align=\"right\" |254\n|-\n|32||{{flag2|Puerto Rico}}|| align=\"right\" |245\n|}\n\n== Social impact ==\nImmigration to [[Costa Rica]] has caused some social problems. Although most people enter the country to seek better employment opportunities, some immigrants have been involved in criminal activities. The government of Costa Rica has tried to stop the illegal immigration of [[Nicaraguans]] and to deport those already living in Costa Rica. However, the government has also initiated programs to promote economic prosperity for the poorest immigrant populations, also hailing from [[Nicaragua]]. There are also a number of political refugees who have sought asylum from persecution in Costa Rica.<ref>''Cepal'' [http://www.cepal.org/es/publicaciones/inmigracion-en-costa-rica-caracteristicas-sociales-y-laborales-integracion-y-politicas Inmigraci\u00f3n en Costa Rica: caracter\u00edsticas sociales y laborales, integraci\u00f3n y pol\u00edticas p\u00fablicas] Retrieved, 11/12/2014.</ref>\n\n== Immigrant groups ==\nThe largest immigrant communities are from [[Nicaragua]] (74.6%), [[Colombia]] (4.3%), the [[United States]] (4.1%), [[Panama]] (2.9%) and [[El Salvador]] (2.4%). The remaining 11.7% are of other nationalities, with significant communities from China (3,281 people), Cuba (3,860 people), Honduras (3,778 people), Peru (3,404 people) and Venezuela (3,886 people).<ref name=inmigranteinec/> Many Europeans have immigrated to Costa Rica in recent years, especially [[Spaniards]], [[Bulgarians]], [[Russians]], [[Ukrainians]], [[Swiss]] and [[Swedish people|Swedish]]. There are also many [[Asians|Asian]] ([[Chinese people|Chinese]], [[Taiwanese people|Taiwanese]] and [[Japanese people|Japanese]]) immigrants. Immigrants may be attracted by political stability, an alternative way of life and a mild climate.\n\n=== Nicaraguans ===\nNicaraguans constitute nearly three-quarters of the foreign-born population of Costa Rica.<ref>https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/cs.html</ref> In 1984, there were 45,918 Nicaraguan-born people in Costa Rica. In 2012, the number had grown to around 287,000.<ref>''Carlos Castro Valverde'' [http://www.prolades.com/cra/regions/cam/cri/migracion_nica.pdf Migraci\u00f3n Nicarag\u00fcense en Costa Rica (Cuadro 2)] 5 December 2002. Retrieved, 11/12/2014.</ref>\n\n=== Colombians ===\nIn recent decades, Costa Rica has become a refuge for thousands of [[Demographics of Colombia|Colombians]] who have fled the [[Colombian conflict (1964\u2013present)|Colombian civil war]].  According to the census of 2012, there are about 20,000 Colombians in Costa Rica, making it the tenth-largest community of Colombians outside the country.  Many Colombian immigrants are educated, which makes it easier for them to achieve dual citizenship.<ref>''Julio Varela Jara'' [http://www.acnur.org/biblioteca/pdf/6305.pdf?view=1 Inmigraci\u00f3n Colombiana en Costa Rica] Retrieved, 11/12/2014.</ref>\n\n=== Spaniards ===\n{{main|Spanish Costa Rican}}\n[[File:Galicia CR.png|234px|thumbnail|Celebration of [[Santiago Ap\u00f3stol]] in Costa Rica.]]\n[[Spanish diaspora|Spanish immigration]] began with the exploration of [[Hern\u00e1n Ponce de Le\u00f3n]] and [[Juan Casta\u00f1eda|Juan de Casta\u00f1eda]] along the Pacific coast in the early sixteenth century, who soon after placed the native population of this region under Spanish control. After independence, the [[governors]] were interested in populating the territories with white workers, preferably imported from [[Europe]].<ref>[http://www.angelfire.com/bc/gonebirding/colony.html La conquista espa\u00f1ola y colonizaci\u00f3n] Retrieved 2014-12-11.</ref> Banana cultivation and labor for the construction of the railway to the Atlantic attracted foreign capital. In the census of 1864, there were only 41 [[Spaniards]] in Costa Rica, however, the number increased to 2,527 by 1927.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mar\u00edn Araya|first1=Guiselle|title=Espa\u00f1oles en la ciudad de San Jos\u00e9 a fines del siglo XIX y principios del XX|trans-title=Spaniards in the city of San Jos\u00e9 at the end of the 19th century and the beginning of the 20th|url=http://revistas.ucr.ac.cr/index.php/anuario/article/view/1938|website=http://revistas.ucr.ac.cr/|publisher=Universidad de Costa Rica|accessdate=23 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the early twentieth century, many Spaniards used Costa Rica as a bridge to move to [[Panama]], attracted by the construction of the [[Panama Canal]]. The events in [[Catalonia]] in the same time period prompted many [[Catalan People|Catalans]] to migrate to Costa Rica, becoming in a few years a thriving and influential community in [[San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|San Jos\u00e9]] that persists today. Currently, Catalans make up the largest portion of Spaniards in Costa Rica. According to the 2009 census<ref name=\"Censo Cerrado\">''Censo electoral de espa\u00f1oles residentes en el extranjero 2009'' [http://www.ine.es/censoe/censo_cerrado/index.html INE-Censo cerrado.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100127104640/http://www.ine.es/censoe/censo_cerrado/index.html|date=2010-01-27}} Retrieved 11/12/2014.</ref>, there are currently 16,482 Spanish citizens in Costa Rica.\n\n=== Americans (US) ===\n{{main|Americans in Costa Rica}}\nOf the 16,000 [[Americans]] in the country, around half of them are under the age of 29. They mainly live in [[San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|San Jos\u00e9]], [[P\u00e9rez Zeled\u00f3n (canton)|P\u00e9rez Zeled\u00f3n]], [[Escaz\u00fa, Costa Rica|Escaz\u00fa]], [[Alajuela]], [[Santa Ana, Costa Rica|Santa Ana]] and [[Santa Cruz Canton, Costa Rica|Santa Cruz]]. American immigrants work in the fields of education, commerce, tourism, and administrative activities. About half of these immigrants have dual citizenship.<ref>''La Naci\u00f3n'' [http://www.nacion.com/nacional/comunidades/mitad-estadounidenses-viven-Costa-Rica_0_1339266173.html La mitad de los estadounidenses que viven en Costa Rica tienen 29 a\u00f1os o menos] Retrieved, 2014/11/12.</ref>\n\n=== Panamanians ===\nAccording to the census of 2012, there are 11,427 [[Panamanians]] in [[Costa Rica]]. They mainly live in [[San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|San Jos\u00e9]]. They form 4.1% of the immigrant population, making them the fifth-largest immigrant community in [[Costa Rica]].\n\n=== Canadians ===\nAccording to the census of 2011, there are about 1,700 [[Canadians]] in [[Costa Rica]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.inec.go.cr/sites/default/files/documentos/poblacion/migracion/estadisticas/resultados/repoblaccenso2011-03.xls.xls|title=Costa Rica: Poblaci\u00f3n total nacida en el extranjero por zona y sexo, seg\u00fan pa\u00eds de nacimiento y a\u00f1o de llegada al pa\u00eds|website=INEC Costa Rica|publisher=National Institute of Statistics And Censuses, Costa Rica|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161010132433/http://www.inec.go.cr/sites/default/files/documentos/poblacion/migracion/estadisticas/resultados/repoblaccenso2011-03.xls.xls|archive-date=2016-10-10|url-status=live|access-date=10 Jul 2018}}</ref>. They mainly come from [[Calgary]], [[Alberta]] and [[Ottawa]]. Many work in tourism and are resident on to the coast near popular beaches while others live in the cities such as [[San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|San Jos\u00e9]] and Santa Ana.<ref>[http://www.welovecostarica.com/public/1606.cfm Canadians Living in Costa Rica] Retrieved, 11/12/2014.</ref>\n\n=== El Salvador ===\nAccording to the census of 2012, there are about 7,189 [[Salvadorans]] in [[Costa Rica]], mainly in [[San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|San Jos\u00e9]]. Many of them are from the upper class and looking to develop their businesses. \n\n=== Hondurans ===\nAccording to the census of 2012, there are 5,669 [[Hondurans]] in [[Costa Rica]], who live mainly in [[San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|San Jos\u00e9]]. Many of these immigrants arrived via [[Nicaragua]].\n\n=== Britons ===\nAfter the [[independence]] of [[Costa Rica]] (1821), the Costa Rican government encouraged foreign immigration to strengthen the workforce. The new arrivals came mainly from [[Central Europe]] and [[North America]], although [[Germans]], [[British people|Britons]] and [[Americans]] also arrived, the latter two known collectively as [[Anglo]]s. [[Great Britain|Britain]] was the first to notice the potential that [[Costa Rica]] had to offer from coffee production; over time, agricultural areas of the Caribbean and northern Costa Rica were under [[British Empire|British]] control, especially the coffee farms. Afterwards the [[British people|Britons]] brought in [[Italians]] for construction of the railroad of Altiplano. Most of the agriculturally productive areas were held by the British.<ref>[http://revistahistoria.historia.ucr.ac.cr/Numeros%20Anteriores/11/Herrera%20Balharry,%20Eugenio.%20Los%20inmigrantes%20y%20el%20poder%20en%20C.R.pdf Los inmigrantes y el poder en Costa Rica] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150703224114/http://revistahistoria.historia.ucr.ac.cr/Numeros%20Anteriores/11/Herrera%20Balharry,%20Eugenio.%20Los%20inmigrantes%20y%20el%20poder%20en%20C.R.pdf |date=2015-07-03 }} ''Pages: 133,134 and 135''. Retrieved, 2014/11/12.</ref>\n\nAccording to the census of 2012, there are about 5,200 [[British people|Britons]] in [[Costa Rica]], forming the second-largest [[European peoples|European]] community after the [[Spaniards]].\n\n=== Chinese ===\n{{main|Chinese people in Costa Rica}}\nThe Chinese community in Costa Rica (including [[Taiwanese people|Taiwanese]]) is the largest Asian community in the country. According with the census of 2012, there are about 4,500 Chinese living in the country. The first [[Chinese immigrants]] arrived in [[Costa Rica]] in 1855. They were a group of 77 people originally from [[Guangzhou|Canton]], who had come to [[Central America]] to work on the [[Panama]] Railroad. During 1859-1863 under the administration of [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Montealegre]], laws were enacted that prohibited the immigration of blacks and Asians, in an effort to preserve [[Costa Rica]] for [[European diaspora|European settlement]].<ref>{{harvnb|Lor\u00eda Chaves|Rodr\u00edguez Chaves|2001}}</ref> Later, \"a Chinese colony\" began to form in that area, founded by Joseph Chen Apuy, an immigrant from [[Zhongshan]], [[Guangdong]], who arrived in 1873. The colony, named [[Puntarenas]], was so well known in China that some thought in error that it was the name of a country.<ref>{{harvnb|Chen Apuy|1992|p=5}}</ref> In the 1970s, [[Taiwan]] became the source of the highest number of Chinese immigrants to Costa Rica. However, many used to Costa Rica as a temporary stop while waiting for permission to live in the [[United States]] or [[Canada]].\n\n=== Mexicans ===\n{{main|Mexicans in Costa Rica}}\nCosta Rica is most popular [[Central American]] country for [[Mexicans|Mexican]] immigration{{citation needed |date=March 2018}}. The waves of migration from [[Mexico]] to [[Costa Rica]] started in 1970s, as people were attracted to its stable democracy, mild climate and political stability. According to the census of 2012, 4,285 Mexicans were living in Costa Rica from [[Nuevo Le\u00f3n]], [[Tamaulipas]], [[Chihuahua (state)|Chihuahua]], [[Baja California]] and [[Mexico City]]. They are typically professionals, doctors, secretaries, among other roles. Costa Rica is the ninth most popular destination for Mexican immigrants in the world.<ref>[http://www.ime.gob.mx/mundo/america.htm Mexicanos en Costa Rica] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120625041450/http://www.ime.gob.mx/mundo/america.htm |date=2012-06-25 }} Retrieved, 2014/11/12.</ref>\n\n=== Venezuelans ===\nAccording to the census of 2012, there are about 3,886 [[Venezuelans]] in [[Costa Rica]] that live mainly in [[San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|San Jos\u00e9]], in the areas of Escaz\u00fa and Santa Ana. Most of them have arrived as refugees from political problems in their country. This population increased significantly from 2015-2019, mostly due the Venezuelan political and economical crisis. Nowadays there are about 15,000 Venezuelans in Costa Rica.\n\n=== Peruvians ===\nThe census of 2012 found that nearly 2,700 [[Peruvians]] were living in [[Costa Rica]]. Some arrived directly from their country of origin, while others had emigrated first to [[Chile]] and then fled the anti-Peruvian sentiment in Chile{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}. Although there are also cases of racism against Peruvians in Costa Rica, they occur to a lesser extent.\n\n=== Chileans ===\nAccording to the census of 2012, there are nearly 2,600 [[Chileans]] living in [[Costa Rica]]. They have mostly settled in urban areas such as [[San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|San Jos\u00e9]].\n\n=== Italians ===\n{{main|Italian Costa Rican}}\n[[File:Costa Rica-Teatro Nacional.JPG|254px|thumbnail|The \"National Theatre\" in San Jose, Costa Rica, was built by the Italian engineer Cristoforo Molinari in 1897. It has a striking resemblance to the ''Temple of the Opera'', La Scala in [[Milan]].]]\n[[Italian diaspora|Italian migration]] to Costa Rica consists of several migratory waves between 1887 and 1888. In February 1887, the US railroad entrepreneur, [[Minor Cooper Keith]], had four hundred men working on a new line, but needed more labor. In October of the same year, following unsuccessful attempts to persuade commissioners in [[Italy]], the [[Canary Islands]] and Cape Verde, Keith traveled to [[London]] to arrange the import of [[Italians|Italian]] workers. On May 10, 1888, the Anna Elise docked in [[Lim\u00f3n, Costa Rica|Lim\u00f3n]] ([[Costa Rica]]). It was carrying 671 workers. These Italians joined other immigrants from China and elsewhere building the first railway line in Costa Rica. The conditions were dangerous, and the [[Italians]] were angered by the deaths of many workers. In October 1888, the Italian workers called a strike, and on 20 October 1888, large numbers deserted the work camps and fled to [[Cartago, Costa Rica|Cartago]] ([[Costa Rica]]), where many settled, but others returned on a ship to Italy. They were replaced by 848 immigrants who came on March 16, 1889.<ref>''Revista Acta Acad\u00e9mica'' [http://www.prolades.com/cra/regions/cam/cri/italiana-4.htm La inmigraci\u00f3n italiana en Costa Rica] Retrieved, 2014/11/12.</ref> Currently, according to the census of 2012, there are 2,300 [[Italians]] in [[Costa Rica]], and their descendants are found in [[Cartago, Costa Rica|Cartago]].\n\n=== Russian and ex-Soviet peoples ===\n[[Russians|Russian]] and Soviet immigration to [[Costa Rica]] occurred during the twentieth century. The arrivals hail in greatest numbers from [[Volga]], [[Belarus]] (including people from [[Ukraine]] and the [[Baltic countries]]), coming as refugees after the [[First World War]] and the [[Cold War]]. A number of Costa Ricans studied in the Soviet Union through scholarships, and came back married to Russians, establishing families in Costa Rica. According to the census of 2012, there are over 2,300 Russians in Costa Rica.\n\n=== Germans ===\nThe immigration of [[Germans]] to [[Costa Rica]] occurred in three main phases: prior to 1871 (the year in which the [[German Empire]] was founded), from 1871 to 1918, at the end of the [[First World War]], and from 1918-1919 until the start of the [[Second World War]] in 1939. The first [[Germans|German]] immigrants arrived between 1825 and 1826. In 1850, the [[German diaspora|German immigration]] was insignificant. In 1864 there were 164 Germans living in Costa Rica. Most were attracted by the growing foreign commerce. Others migrated because of the economic situation facing [[Germany]] in the 1840s and the failed revolution in 1848. Then came another group in the late nineteenth century. There were new infrastructure projects, and existing personal networks between [[Germany]] and [[Costa Rica]] helped to increase immigration. Before the [[First World War]], there was already a German Club, founded in 1910, and the German School which started in 1912. At the beginning of the [[Second World War]], a third group of immigrants arrived. After the war, relations were broken between two countries, and many naturalized [[Germans]] after the war no longer appear in the statistics.<ref>''Business Magazine'' [https://web.archive.org/web/20140321182915/http://business.highbeam.com/1033/article-1G1-183042711/la-inmigraci-n-alemana-en-costa-rica-migraci-n-crisis La inmigraci\u00f3n alemana en Costa Rica. Migraci\u00f3n, crisis y cambios entre 1920 y 1950 en entrevistas con descendientes Alemanes.] Retrieved, 2014/11/12.</ref> Currently the census of 2012 states there are 2,100 [[Germans]] in [[Costa Rica]].\n\n=== Polish ===\n[[Polish diaspora|Polish immigration]] to [[Costa Rica]] occurred from 1929 to 1941. In 1929, about fifteen Poles arrived in Costa Rica, with the number rising to 90 in 1930. Among the first Polish arrivals were Jewish immigrants Jacobo Schifter and Lollew Gudmundson, who left their country to settle in [[Costa Rica]] This became a motivator for many more Poles to go Costa Rica. The largest wave of immigration of [[Poles]] to [[Costa Rica]] was between 1933 and 1936. Xenophobia developed in Costa Rica, because most of the [[Poles]] were of [[Jewish]] origin. The [[Poles]] in [[Costa Rica]] were engaged in the home industry and small businesses. Later, around 1939, several waves of [[Jewish]] [[Polish people|Polish]] families fleeing the [[Nazi]] repression arrived. Others followed after the war. By the 1950s, the majority left the country to emigrate to [[Mexico]] or [[Argentina]].<ref>[http://www.cesla.uw.edu.pl/www/images/stories/wydawnictwo/czasopisma/Revista/Revista_4/172-189_Sotoquiros.pdf Polacos judios y xenofobia en Costa Rica: 1929 - 1941] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140419014714/http://www.cesla.uw.edu.pl/www/images/stories/wydawnictwo/czasopisma/Revista/Revista_4/172-189_Sotoquiros.pdf |date=2014-04-19 }} Retrieved, 2014/11/12.</ref> Currently the census of 2012 says there are 1,900 [[Poles]] in [[Costa Rica]].\n\n=== Cubans ===\nAccording to the census of 2012, there are over 1,700 [[Cubans]] living in [[Costa Rica]]. Immigration began from the 1960s through boats of refugees fleeing the dictatorship of [[Fidel Castro]]. They were attracted by the political stability of Costa Rica.\n\n=== Swiss ===\n[[Swiss]] people have immigrated to Costa Rica since the nineteenth century, and have been involved in the development of [[Costa Rican]] chocolate. According to the census of 2012, there are about 1,642 [[Swiss]] in [[Costa Rica]]{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}.\n\n=== Dominicans ===\nAccording to the census of 2012, there are about 1,475 [[People of the Dominican Republic|Dominicans]] in [[Costa Rica]]. They mainly live on the Caribbean coast.\n\n=== Brazilians ===\nAccording to the census of 2012, there are about 1,300 [[Brazilians]] in [[Costa Rica]]. Many of those who come are actors, actresses, models and television hosts. The [[Brazilians]] in [[Costa Rica]] live mainly in the expensive hotels in [[San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|San Jos\u00e9]]{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}.\n\n=== Belizeans ===\nAccording to the census of 2012, there are about 1,275 [[Belizeans]] in [[Costa Rica]]. Many have arrived as part of the [[Mormon]] missions.{{citations needed|date=March 2018}}.\n\n=== Guatemalans ===\nAccording to the census of 2012, there are about 1,200 [[Demographics of Guatemala|Guatemalans]] in [[Costa Rica]]. There are both economic and political migrants. Most live in [[San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|San Jos\u00e9]].\n\n=== Uruguayans ===\nAccording to the census of 2012, there are about 1,200 [[Uruguayans]] in [[Costa Rica]]. This country has recently proved attractive for [[Uruguayans]] entrepreneurs.\n\n=== Argentines ===\n[[Costa Rica]] is the country with the highest population of Argentines in Central America. According to the census of 2012, there were 3,600 Argentines living in Costa Rica. Historically there were two migratory waves of refugees escaping from [[military dictatorships]] who ruled [[Argentina]] between 1976 and 1983. A second wave occurred during Argentina's economic crisis (1999-2002), when many [[Argentine]] professionals decided to migrate to [[Costa Rica]]. The largest numbers of  Argentines in Costa Rica come from [[Buenos Aires]], [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]] and [[Rosario]]. Most of them reside in the provinces of [[San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|San Jos\u00e9]], [[Cartago, Costa Rica|Cartago]], [[Lim\u00f3n Province|Lim\u00f3n]] and [[Guanacaste Province|Guanacaste]].\n\n=== French ===\n[[French diaspora|French immigration]] in [[Costa Rica]] began in the 1840s. Following the victory of liberal governments, it became easier for painters, musicians and French singers to immigrate. France has contributed greatly to [[Costa Rican]] culture and influence. French composer Gabriel-Pierre Lafond was in part responsible for the national anthem of Costa Rica, the primary composer of which was Manuel Mar\u00eda Guti\u00e9rrez. The Museum of Art was created by French sculptor Louis-Robert Carrier Belleuse, and the [[flag of Costa Rica]] was inspired by the [[flag of France]].<ref>''Ministerio de Relaciones Exteriores, Rep\u00fablica de Costa Rica'' [http://www.rree.go.cr/?sec=relaciones%20bilaterales&cat=relaciones%20bilaterales%20por%20pais&cont=522&codpais=FR Relaci\u00f3n de Costa Rica con Francia] Retrieved, 2014/11/12.</ref> Costa Rica is home to about 1,000 French people, according to the census of 2012.\n\n=== Ecuadorians ===\nAccording to the census of 2012, there are about 900 [[Demographics of Ecuador|Ecuadorians]] in [[Costa Rica]]. Among these are television presenters, models or entrepreneurs, commonly living in the city of [[San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|San Jos\u00e9]].\n\n=== South Koreans ===\nKorean immigration is a recent phenomenon in [[Central America]]. The first [[Koreans]] came to Costa Rica in the 1990s, working in the clothing, automobile, restaurant and transportation businesses. There are many institutes and Korean associations. With a high percentage of [[Protestants]] among the population, some are missionaries of the Korean church.<ref>[http://cri.mofa.go.kr/webmodule/htsboard/template/read/legengreadboard.jsp?typeID=16&boardid=14039&seqno=688111&c=&t=&pagenum=1&tableName=TYPE_ENGLEGATIO&pc=&dc=&wc=&lu=&vu=&iu=&du= Historia de la migraci\u00f3n coreana] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20141212003828/http://cri.mofa.go.kr/webmodule/htsboard/template/read/legengreadboard.jsp?typeID=16&boardid=14039&seqno=688111&c=&t=&pagenum=1&tableName=TYPE_ENGLEGATIO&pc=&dc=&wc=&lu=&vu=&iu=&du= |date=2014-12-12 }} Retrieved, 2014/11/12.</ref> The Korean community is not large in Costa Rica, comprising 522 residents according to the census of 2012.\n\n=== Japanese ===\nAccording to the census of 2012, the [[Demographics of Japan|Japanese]] community in [[Costa Rica]] amounts to 190 people. The Japanese have developed many technological companies in the country.\n\n=== Haitians ===\nAccording to the census of 2012, the [[Haitians|Haitian]] community consists of 150 residents. \n\n=== Indians ===\nAs of December 2016, the Indian community in Costa Rica consists of 250 residents,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mea.gov.in/images/pdf/NRIs-and-PIOs.pdf|title=MEA - GOI|last=|first=|date=|website=MEA - Government of India|access-date=}}</ref> primarily employed in the country's IT industry. Out of these, twenty have renounced Indian citizenship and hold [[Persons of Indian Origin Card|PIO cards]].\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Demographics of Costa Rica]]\n* [http://www.sircostarica.com/ Costa Rica Real Estate, Cost of Living and Real Estate Law]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Notes ==\n*1. ''The statistics of this page comes from the Wikipedia page in Spanish [[:es:Costa Rica#Demograf.C3.ADa|(Costa Rica) in section demography]].''\n*2.''some sections are partial translations of the Spanish Wikipedia page [[:es:Inmigraci\u00f3n en Costa Rica|(Inmigracion en Costa Rica)]] [https://es.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Inmigraci%C3%B3n_en_Costa_Rica&action=history and its creators].''\n\n{{Ethnic groups in Costa Rica}}\n{{North America in topic|Immigration to}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Immigration To Costa Rica}}\n[[Category:Demographics of Costa Rica]]\n", "text_old": "As of the 2011 census, the number of '''immigrants in Costa Rica''' totaled about 390,000 individuals, or about 9% of the country's population.<ref name=inmigranteinec>{{cite web|title=Costa Rica: Poblaci\u00f3n total nacida en el extranjero por zona y sexo, seg\u00fan pa\u00eds de nacimiento y a\u00f1o de llegada al pa\u00eds|url=http://www.inec.go.cr/sites/default/files/documentos/poblacion/migracion/estadisticas/resultados/repoblaccenso2011-03.xls.xls|website=Instituto Nacional de Estad\u00edstica y Censos|accessdate=27 December 2017|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Costa Rica: Poblaci\u00f3n total por lugar de nacimiento, seg\u00fan provincia de residencia actual y sexo|url=http://www.inec.go.cr/sites/default/files/documentos/poblacion/estadisticas/resultados/repoblaccenso2011-04.xls.xls|website=Instituto Nacional de Estad\u00edstica y Censos|accessdate=27 December 2017|language=Spanish}}</ref> Following a considerable drop from 1950 through 1980, immigration to [[Costa Rica]] has increased in recent decades.\n\nThe ethnic composition of Costa Rica consists mostly of people of [[European Costa Rican|European]] origin, with a large population of [[Mestizos]] and numerically fewer [[Afro-Costa Rican|black]] and [[Indigenous peoples of Costa Rica|indigenous]] people.\n\n{| class=\"toc\" cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=20% style=\"float:right; text-align:left;clear:all; margin-left:20px; font-size:90%;\"\n!bgcolor=black colspan=8 style=\"color:white;\"|total foreign population 2012<ref name=inmigranteinec/>\n|- bgcolor=\"#efefef\"\n!Place.\n!Country.\n!Numbers.\n|-\n|1||{{flag2|Nicaragua}}|| align=\"right\" |287&nbsp;766\n|-\n|2||{{flag2|Colombia}}|| align=\"right\" |16&nbsp;514\n|-\n|3||{{flag2|United States}}|| align=\"right\" |15&nbsp;898\n|-\n|4||{{flag2|Panama}}|| align=\"right\" |11&nbsp;250\n|-\n|5||{{flag2|El Salvador}}|| align=\"right\" |9&nbsp;424\n|-\n|6||{{flag2|Venezuela}}|| align=\"right\" |&nbsp;3 886\n|-\n|7||{{flag2|Cuba}}|| align=\"right\" |3&nbsp;860\n|-\n|8||{{flag2|Honduras}}|| align=\"right\" |3&nbsp;778\n|-\n|9||{{flag2|Peru}}|| align=\"right\" |3&nbsp;404\n|-\n|10||{{flag2|China}}|| align=\"right\" |3&nbsp;281\n|-\n|11||{{flag2|Mexico}}|| align=\"right\" |3&nbsp;059\n|-\n|12||{{flag2|Guatemala}}|| align=\"right\" | 2 573\n|-\n|13||{{flag2|Spain}}|| align=\"right\" |&nbsp;1 806\n|-\n|14||{{flag2|Argentina}}|| align=\"right\" |1&nbsp;786\n|-\n|15||{{flag2|Canada}}|| align=\"right\" |&nbsp;1 679\n|-\n|16||{{flag2|Italy}}|| align=\"right\" |1&nbsp;494\n|-\n|17||{{flag2|Dominican Republic}}|| align=\"right\" |1&nbsp;475\n|-\n|18||{{flag2|Germany}}|| align=\"right\" |1&nbsp;412\n|-\n|19||{{flag2|Chile}}|| align=\"right\" |1&nbsp;364\n|-\n|20||{{flag2|Ecuador}}|| align=\"right\" |1&nbsp;040\n|-\n|21||{{flag2|France}}|| align=\"right\" |936\n|-\n|22||{{flag2|Taiwan}}|| align=\"right\" |797\n|-\n|23||{{flag2|Brazil}}|| align=\"right\" |605\n|-\n|24||{{flag2|Switzerland}}|| align=\"right\" |551\n|-\n|25||{{flag2|England}}|| align=\"right\" |503\n|-\n|26||{{flag2|Netherlands}}|| align=\"right\" |434\n|-\n|27||{{flag2|Russia}}|| align=\"right\" |429\n|-\n|28||{{flag2|Uruguay}}|| align=\"right\" |356\n|-\n|29||{{flag2|Bolivia}}|| align=\"right\" |331\n|-\n|30||{{flag2|South Korea}}|| align=\"right\" |263\n|-\n|31||{{flag2|Belgium}}|| align=\"right\" |254\n|-\n|32||{{flag2|Puerto Rico}}|| align=\"right\" |245\n|}\n\n== Social impact ==\nImmigration to [[Costa Rica]] has caused some social problems. Although most people enter the country to seek better employment opportunities, some immigrants have been involved in criminal activities. The government of Costa Rica has tried to stop the illegal immigration of [[Nicaraguans]] and to deport those already living in Costa Rica. However, the government has also initiated programs to promote economic prosperity for the poorest immigrant populations, also hailing from [[Nicaragua]]. There are also a number of political refugees who have sought asylum from persecution in Costa Rica.<ref>''Cepal'' [http://www.cepal.org/es/publicaciones/inmigracion-en-costa-rica-caracteristicas-sociales-y-laborales-integracion-y-politicas Inmigraci\u00f3n en Costa Rica: caracter\u00edsticas sociales y laborales, integraci\u00f3n y pol\u00edticas p\u00fablicas] Retrieved, 11/12/2014.</ref>\n\n== Immigrant groups ==\nThe largest immigrant communities are from [[Nicaragua]] (74.6%), [[Colombia]] (4.3%), the [[United States]] (4.1%), [[Panama]] (2.9%) and [[El Salvador]] (2.4%). The remaining 11.7% are of other nationalities, with significant communities from China (3,281 people), Cuba (3,860 people), Honduras (3,778 people), Peru (3,404 people) and Venezuela (3,886 people).<ref name=inmigranteinec/> Many [[Europeans]] have immigrated to Costa Rica in recent years, especially [[Spaniards]], [[Bulgarians]], [[Russians]], [[Ukrainians]], [[Swiss]] and [[Swedish people|Swedish]]. There are also many [[Asians|Asian]] ([[Chinese people|Chinese]], [[Taiwanese people|Taiwanese]] and [[Japanese people|Japanese]]) immigrants. Immigrants may be attracted by political stability, an alternative way of life and a mild climate.\n\n=== Nicaraguans ===\nNicaraguans constitute nearly three-quarters of the foreign-born population of Costa Rica.<ref>https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/cs.html</ref> In 1984, there were 45,918 Nicaraguan-born people in Costa Rica. In 2012, the number had grown to around 287,000.<ref>''Carlos Castro Valverde'' [http://www.prolades.com/cra/regions/cam/cri/migracion_nica.pdf Migraci\u00f3n Nicarag\u00fcense en Costa Rica (Cuadro 2)] 5 December 2002. Retrieved, 11/12/2014.</ref>\n\n=== Colombians ===\nIn recent decades, Costa Rica has become a refuge for thousands of [[Demographics of Colombia|Colombians]] who have fled the [[Colombian conflict (1964\u2013present)|Colombian civil war]].  According to the census of 2012, there are about 20,000 Colombians in Costa Rica, making it the tenth-largest community of Colombians outside the country.  Many Colombian immigrants are educated, which makes it easier for them to achieve dual citizenship.<ref>''Julio Varela Jara'' [http://www.acnur.org/biblioteca/pdf/6305.pdf?view=1 Inmigraci\u00f3n Colombiana en Costa Rica] Retrieved, 11/12/2014.</ref>\n\n=== Spaniards ===\n{{main|Spanish Costa Rican}}\n[[File:Galicia CR.png|234px|thumbnail|Celebration of [[Santiago Ap\u00f3stol]] in Costa Rica.]]\n[[Spanish diaspora|Spanish immigration]] began with the exploration of [[Hern\u00e1n Ponce de Le\u00f3n]] and [[Juan Casta\u00f1eda|Juan de Casta\u00f1eda]] along the Pacific coast in the early sixteenth century, who soon after placed the native population of this region under Spanish control. After independence, the [[governors]] were interested in populating the territories with white workers, preferably imported from [[Europe]].<ref>[http://www.angelfire.com/bc/gonebirding/colony.html La conquista espa\u00f1ola y colonizaci\u00f3n] Retrieved 2014-12-11.</ref> Banana cultivation and labor for the construction of the railway to the Atlantic attracted foreign capital. In the census of 1864, there were only 41 [[Spaniards]] in Costa Rica, however, the number increased to 2,527 by 1927.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mar\u00edn Araya|first1=Guiselle|title=Espa\u00f1oles en la ciudad de San Jos\u00e9 a fines del siglo XIX y principios del XX|trans-title=Spaniards in the city of San Jos\u00e9 at the end of the 19th century and the beginning of the 20th|url=http://revistas.ucr.ac.cr/index.php/anuario/article/view/1938|website=http://revistas.ucr.ac.cr/|publisher=Universidad de Costa Rica|accessdate=23 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the early twentieth century, many Spaniards used Costa Rica as a bridge to move to [[Panama]], attracted by the construction of the [[Panama Canal]]. The events in [[Catalonia]] in the same time period prompted many [[Catalan People|Catalans]] to migrate to Costa Rica, becoming in a few years a thriving and influential community in [[San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|San Jos\u00e9]] that persists today. Currently, Catalans make up the largest portion of Spaniards in Costa Rica. According to the 2009 census<ref name=\"Censo Cerrado\">''Censo electoral de espa\u00f1oles residentes en el extranjero 2009'' [http://www.ine.es/censoe/censo_cerrado/index.html INE-Censo cerrado.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100127104640/http://www.ine.es/censoe/censo_cerrado/index.html|date=2010-01-27}} Retrieved 11/12/2014.</ref>, there are currently 16,482 Spanish citizens in Costa Rica.\n\n=== Americans (US) ===\n{{main|Americans in Costa Rica}}\nOf the 16,000 [[Americans]] in the country, around half of them are under the age of 29. They mainly live in [[San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|San Jos\u00e9]], [[P\u00e9rez Zeled\u00f3n (canton)|P\u00e9rez Zeled\u00f3n]], [[Escaz\u00fa, Costa Rica|Escaz\u00fa]], [[Alajuela]], [[Santa Ana, Costa Rica|Santa Ana]] and [[Santa Cruz Canton, Costa Rica|Santa Cruz]]. American immigrants work in the fields of education, commerce, tourism, and administrative activities. About half of these immigrants have dual citizenship.<ref>''La Naci\u00f3n'' [http://www.nacion.com/nacional/comunidades/mitad-estadounidenses-viven-Costa-Rica_0_1339266173.html La mitad de los estadounidenses que viven en Costa Rica tienen 29 a\u00f1os o menos] Retrieved, 2014/11/12.</ref>\n\n=== Panamanians ===\nAccording to the census of 2012, there are 11,427 [[Panamanians]] in [[Costa Rica]]. They mainly live in [[San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|San Jos\u00e9]]. They form 4.1% of the immigrant population, making them the fifth-largest immigrant community in [[Costa Rica]].\n\n=== Canadians ===\nAccording to the census of 2011, there are about 1,700 [[Canadians]] in [[Costa Rica]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.inec.go.cr/sites/default/files/documentos/poblacion/migracion/estadisticas/resultados/repoblaccenso2011-03.xls.xls|title=Costa Rica: Poblaci\u00f3n total nacida en el extranjero por zona y sexo, seg\u00fan pa\u00eds de nacimiento y a\u00f1o de llegada al pa\u00eds|website=INEC Costa Rica|publisher=National Institute of Statistics And Censuses, Costa Rica|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161010132433/http://www.inec.go.cr/sites/default/files/documentos/poblacion/migracion/estadisticas/resultados/repoblaccenso2011-03.xls.xls|archive-date=2016-10-10|url-status=live|access-date=10 Jul 2018}}</ref>. They mainly come from [[Calgary]], [[Alberta]] and [[Ottawa]]. Many work in tourism and are resident on to the coast near popular beaches while others live in the cities such as [[San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|San Jos\u00e9]] and Santa Ana.<ref>[http://www.welovecostarica.com/public/1606.cfm Canadians Living in Costa Rica] Retrieved, 11/12/2014.</ref>\n\n=== El Salvador ===\nAccording to the census of 2012, there are about 7,189 [[Salvadorans]] in [[Costa Rica]], mainly in [[San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|San Jos\u00e9]]. Many of them are from the upper class and looking to develop their businesses. \n\n=== Hondurans ===\nAccording to the census of 2012, there are 5,669 [[Hondurans]] in [[Costa Rica]], who live mainly in [[San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|San Jos\u00e9]]. Many of these immigrants arrived via [[Nicaragua]].\n\n=== Britons ===\nAfter the [[independence]] of [[Costa Rica]] (1821), the Costa Rican government encouraged foreign immigration to strengthen the workforce. The new arrivals came mainly from [[Central Europe]] and [[North America]], although [[Germans]], [[British people|Britons]] and [[Americans]] also arrived, the latter two known collectively as [[Anglo]]s. [[Great Britain|Britain]] was the first to notice the potential that [[Costa Rica]] had to offer from coffee production; over time, agricultural areas of the Caribbean and northern Costa Rica were under [[British Empire|British]] control, especially the coffee farms. Afterwards the [[British people|Britons]] brought in [[Italians]] for construction of the railroad of Altiplano. Most of the agriculturally productive areas were held by the British.<ref>[http://revistahistoria.historia.ucr.ac.cr/Numeros%20Anteriores/11/Herrera%20Balharry,%20Eugenio.%20Los%20inmigrantes%20y%20el%20poder%20en%20C.R.pdf Los inmigrantes y el poder en Costa Rica] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150703224114/http://revistahistoria.historia.ucr.ac.cr/Numeros%20Anteriores/11/Herrera%20Balharry,%20Eugenio.%20Los%20inmigrantes%20y%20el%20poder%20en%20C.R.pdf |date=2015-07-03 }} ''Pages: 133,134 and 135''. Retrieved, 2014/11/12.</ref>\n\nAccording to the census of 2012, there are about 5,200 [[British people|Britons]] in [[Costa Rica]], forming the second-largest [[European peoples|European]] community after the [[Spaniards]].\n\n=== Chinese ===\n{{main|Chinese people in Costa Rica}}\nThe Chinese community in Costa Rica (including [[Taiwanese people|Taiwanese]]) is the largest Asian community in the country. According with the census of 2012, there are about 4,500 Chinese living in the country. The first [[Chinese immigrants]] arrived in [[Costa Rica]] in 1855. They were a group of 77 people originally from [[Guangzhou|Canton]], who had come to [[Central America]] to work on the [[Panama]] Railroad. During 1859-1863 under the administration of [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Montealegre]], laws were enacted that prohibited the immigration of blacks and Asians, in an effort to preserve [[Costa Rica]] for [[European diaspora|European settlement]].<ref>{{harvnb|Lor\u00eda Chaves|Rodr\u00edguez Chaves|2001}}</ref> Later, \"a Chinese colony\" began to form in that area, founded by Joseph Chen Apuy, an immigrant from [[Zhongshan]], [[Guangdong]], who arrived in 1873. The colony, named [[Puntarenas]], was so well known in China that some thought in error that it was the name of a country.<ref>{{harvnb|Chen Apuy|1992|p=5}}</ref> In the 1970s, [[Taiwan]] became the source of the highest number of Chinese immigrants to Costa Rica. However, many used to Costa Rica as a temporary stop while waiting for permission to live in the [[United States]] or [[Canada]].\n\n=== Mexicans ===\n{{main|Mexicans in Costa Rica}}\nCosta Rica is most popular [[Central American]] country for [[Mexicans|Mexican]] immigration{{citation needed |date=March 2018}}. The waves of migration from [[Mexico]] to [[Costa Rica]] started in 1970s, as people were attracted to its stable democracy, mild climate and political stability. According to the census of 2012, 4,285 Mexicans were living in Costa Rica from [[Nuevo Le\u00f3n]], [[Tamaulipas]], [[Chihuahua (state)|Chihuahua]], [[Baja California]] and [[Mexico City]]. They are typically professionals, doctors, secretaries, among other roles. Costa Rica is the ninth most popular destination for Mexican immigrants in the world.<ref>[http://www.ime.gob.mx/mundo/america.htm Mexicanos en Costa Rica] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120625041450/http://www.ime.gob.mx/mundo/america.htm |date=2012-06-25 }} Retrieved, 2014/11/12.</ref>\n\n=== Venezuelans ===\nAccording to the census of 2012, there are about 3,886 [[Venezuelans]] in [[Costa Rica]] that live mainly in [[San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|San Jos\u00e9]], in the areas of Escaz\u00fa and Santa Ana. Most of them have arrived as refugees from political problems in their country. This population increased significantly from 2015-2019, mostly due the Venezuelan political and economical crisis. Nowadays there are about 15,000 Venezuelans in Costa Rica.\n\n=== Peruvians ===\nThe census of 2012 found that nearly 2,700 [[Peruvians]] were living in [[Costa Rica]]. Some arrived directly from their country of origin, while others had emigrated first to [[Chile]] and then fled the anti-Peruvian sentiment in Chile{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}. Although there are also cases of racism against Peruvians in Costa Rica, they occur to a lesser extent.\n\n=== Chileans ===\nAccording to the census of 2012, there are nearly 2,600 [[Chileans]] living in [[Costa Rica]]. They have mostly settled in urban areas such as [[San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|San Jos\u00e9]].\n\n=== Italians ===\n{{main|Italian Costa Rican}}\n[[File:Costa Rica-Teatro Nacional.JPG|254px|thumbnail|The \"National Theatre\" in San Jose, Costa Rica, was built by the Italian engineer Cristoforo Molinari in 1897. It has a striking resemblance to the ''Temple of the Opera'', La Scala in [[Milan]].]]\n[[Italian diaspora|Italian migration]] to Costa Rica consists of several migratory waves between 1887 and 1888. In February 1887, the US railroad entrepreneur, [[Minor Cooper Keith]], had four hundred men working on a new line, but needed more labor. In October of the same year, following unsuccessful attempts to persuade commissioners in [[Italy]], the [[Canary Islands]] and Cape Verde, Keith traveled to [[London]] to arrange the import of [[Italians|Italian]] workers. On May 10, 1888, the Anna Elise docked in [[Lim\u00f3n, Costa Rica|Lim\u00f3n]] ([[Costa Rica]]). It was carrying 671 workers. These Italians joined other immigrants from China and elsewhere building the first railway line in Costa Rica. The conditions were dangerous, and the [[Italians]] were angered by the deaths of many workers. In October 1888, the Italian workers called a strike, and on 20 October 1888, large numbers deserted the work camps and fled to [[Cartago, Costa Rica|Cartago]] ([[Costa Rica]]), where many settled, but others returned on a ship to Italy. They were replaced by 848 immigrants who came on March 16, 1889.<ref>''Revista Acta Acad\u00e9mica'' [http://www.prolades.com/cra/regions/cam/cri/italiana-4.htm La inmigraci\u00f3n italiana en Costa Rica] Retrieved, 2014/11/12.</ref> Currently, according to the census of 2012, there are 2,300 [[Italians]] in [[Costa Rica]], and their descendants are found in [[Cartago, Costa Rica|Cartago]].\n\n=== Russian and ex-Soviet peoples ===\n[[Russians|Russian]] and Soviet immigration to [[Costa Rica]] occurred during the twentieth century. The arrivals hail in greatest numbers from [[Volga]], [[Belarus]] (including people from [[Ukraine]] and the [[Baltic countries]]), coming as refugees after the [[First World War]] and the [[Cold War]]. A number of Costa Ricans studied in the Soviet Union through scholarships, and came back married to Russians, establishing families in Costa Rica. According to the census of 2012, there are over 2,300 Russians in Costa Rica.\n\n=== Germans ===\nThe immigration of [[Germans]] to [[Costa Rica]] occurred in three main phases: prior to 1871 (the year in which the [[German Empire]] was founded), from 1871 to 1918, at the end of the [[First World War]], and from 1918-1919 until the start of the [[Second World War]] in 1939. The first [[Germans|German]] immigrants arrived between 1825 and 1826. In 1850, the [[German diaspora|German immigration]] was insignificant. In 1864 there were 164 Germans living in Costa Rica. Most were attracted by the growing foreign commerce. Others migrated because of the economic situation facing [[Germany]] in the 1840s and the failed revolution in 1848. Then came another group in the late nineteenth century. There were new infrastructure projects, and existing personal networks between [[Germany]] and [[Costa Rica]] helped to increase immigration. Before the [[First World War]], there was already a German Club, founded in 1910, and the German School which started in 1912. At the beginning of the [[Second World War]], a third group of immigrants arrived. After the war, relations were broken between two countries, and many naturalized [[Germans]] after the war no longer appear in the statistics.<ref>''Business Magazine'' [https://web.archive.org/web/20140321182915/http://business.highbeam.com/1033/article-1G1-183042711/la-inmigraci-n-alemana-en-costa-rica-migraci-n-crisis La inmigraci\u00f3n alemana en Costa Rica. Migraci\u00f3n, crisis y cambios entre 1920 y 1950 en entrevistas con descendientes Alemanes.] Retrieved, 2014/11/12.</ref> Currently the census of 2012 states there are 2,100 [[Germans]] in [[Costa Rica]].\n\n=== Polish ===\n[[Polish diaspora|Polish immigration]] to [[Costa Rica]] occurred from 1929 to 1941. In 1929, about fifteen Poles arrived in Costa Rica, with the number rising to 90 in 1930. Among the first Polish arrivals were Jewish immigrants Jacobo Schifter and Lollew Gudmundson, who left their country to settle in [[Costa Rica]] This became a motivator for many more Poles to go Costa Rica. The largest wave of immigration of [[Poles]] to [[Costa Rica]] was between 1933 and 1936. Xenophobia developed in Costa Rica, because most of the [[Poles]] were of [[Jewish]] origin. The [[Poles]] in [[Costa Rica]] were engaged in the home industry and small businesses. Later, around 1939, several waves of [[Jewish]] [[Polish people|Polish]] families fleeing the [[Nazi]] repression arrived. Others followed after the war. By the 1950s, the majority left the country to emigrate to [[Mexico]] or [[Argentina]].<ref>[http://www.cesla.uw.edu.pl/www/images/stories/wydawnictwo/czasopisma/Revista/Revista_4/172-189_Sotoquiros.pdf Polacos judios y xenofobia en Costa Rica: 1929 - 1941] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140419014714/http://www.cesla.uw.edu.pl/www/images/stories/wydawnictwo/czasopisma/Revista/Revista_4/172-189_Sotoquiros.pdf |date=2014-04-19 }} Retrieved, 2014/11/12.</ref> Currently the census of 2012 says there are 1,900 [[Poles]] in [[Costa Rica]].\n\n=== Cubans ===\nAccording to the census of 2012, there are over 1,700 [[Cubans]] living in [[Costa Rica]]. Immigration began from the 1960s through boats of refugees fleeing the dictatorship of [[Fidel Castro]]. They were attracted by the political stability of Costa Rica.\n\n=== Swiss ===\n[[Swiss]] people have immigrated to Costa Rica since the nineteenth century, and have been involved in the development of [[Costa Rican]] chocolate. According to the census of 2012, there are about 1,642 [[Swiss]] in [[Costa Rica]]{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}.\n\n=== Dominicans ===\nAccording to the census of 2012, there are about 1,475 [[People of the Dominican Republic|Dominicans]] in [[Costa Rica]]. They mainly live on the Caribbean coast.\n\n=== Brazilians ===\nAccording to the census of 2012, there are about 1,300 [[Brazilians]] in [[Costa Rica]]. Many of those who come are actors, actresses, models and television hosts. The [[Brazilians]] in [[Costa Rica]] live mainly in the expensive hotels in [[San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|San Jos\u00e9]]{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}.\n\n=== Belizeans ===\nAccording to the census of 2012, there are about 1,275 [[Belizeans]] in [[Costa Rica]]. Many have arrived as part of the [[Mormon]] missions.{{citations needed|date=March 2018}}.\n\n=== Guatemalans ===\nAccording to the census of 2012, there are about 1,200 [[Demographics of Guatemala|Guatemalans]] in [[Costa Rica]]. There are both economic and political migrants. Most live in [[San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|San Jos\u00e9]].\n\n=== Uruguayans ===\nAccording to the census of 2012, there are about 1,200 [[Uruguayans]] in [[Costa Rica]]. This country has recently proved attractive for [[Uruguayans]] entrepreneurs.\n\n=== Argentines ===\n[[Costa Rica]] is the country with the highest population of Argentines in Central America. According to the census of 2012, there were 3,600 Argentines living in Costa Rica. Historically there were two migratory waves of refugees escaping from [[military dictatorships]] who ruled [[Argentina]] between 1976 and 1983. A second wave occurred during Argentina's economic crisis (1999-2002), when many [[Argentine]] professionals decided to migrate to [[Costa Rica]]. The largest numbers of  Argentines in Costa Rica come from [[Buenos Aires]], [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]] and [[Rosario]]. Most of them reside in the provinces of [[San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|San Jos\u00e9]], [[Cartago, Costa Rica|Cartago]], [[Lim\u00f3n Province|Lim\u00f3n]] and [[Guanacaste Province|Guanacaste]].\n\n=== French ===\n[[French diaspora|French immigration]] in [[Costa Rica]] began in the 1840s. Following the victory of liberal governments, it became easier for painters, musicians and French singers to immigrate. France has contributed greatly to [[Costa Rican]] culture and influence. French composer Gabriel-Pierre Lafond was in part responsible for the national anthem of Costa Rica, the primary composer of which was Manuel Mar\u00eda Guti\u00e9rrez. The Museum of Art was created by French sculptor Louis-Robert Carrier Belleuse, and the [[flag of Costa Rica]] was inspired by the [[flag of France]].<ref>''Ministerio de Relaciones Exteriores, Rep\u00fablica de Costa Rica'' [http://www.rree.go.cr/?sec=relaciones%20bilaterales&cat=relaciones%20bilaterales%20por%20pais&cont=522&codpais=FR Relaci\u00f3n de Costa Rica con Francia] Retrieved, 2014/11/12.</ref> Costa Rica is home to about 1,000 French people, according to the census of 2012.\n\n=== Ecuadorians ===\nAccording to the census of 2012, there are about 900 [[Demographics of Ecuador|Ecuadorians]] in [[Costa Rica]]. Among these are television presenters, models or entrepreneurs, commonly living in the city of [[San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|San Jos\u00e9]].\n\n=== South Koreans ===\nKorean immigration is a recent phenomenon in [[Central America]]. The first [[Koreans]] came to Costa Rica in the 1990s, working in the clothing, automobile, restaurant and transportation businesses. There are many institutes and Korean associations. With a high percentage of [[Protestants]] among the population, some are missionaries of the Korean church.<ref>[http://cri.mofa.go.kr/webmodule/htsboard/template/read/legengreadboard.jsp?typeID=16&boardid=14039&seqno=688111&c=&t=&pagenum=1&tableName=TYPE_ENGLEGATIO&pc=&dc=&wc=&lu=&vu=&iu=&du= Historia de la migraci\u00f3n coreana] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20141212003828/http://cri.mofa.go.kr/webmodule/htsboard/template/read/legengreadboard.jsp?typeID=16&boardid=14039&seqno=688111&c=&t=&pagenum=1&tableName=TYPE_ENGLEGATIO&pc=&dc=&wc=&lu=&vu=&iu=&du= |date=2014-12-12 }} Retrieved, 2014/11/12.</ref> The Korean community is not large in Costa Rica, comprising 522 residents according to the census of 2012.\n\n=== Japanese ===\nAccording to the census of 2012, the [[Demographics of Japan|Japanese]] community in [[Costa Rica]] amounts to 190 people. The Japanese have developed many technological companies in the country.\n\n=== Haitians ===\nAccording to the census of 2012, the [[Haitians|Haitian]] community consists of 150 residents. \n\n=== Indians ===\nAs of December 2016, the Indian community in Costa Rica consists of 250 residents,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mea.gov.in/images/pdf/NRIs-and-PIOs.pdf|title=MEA - GOI|last=|first=|date=|website=MEA - Government of India|access-date=}}</ref> primarily employed in the country's IT industry. Out of these, twenty have renounced Indian citizenship and hold [[Persons of Indian Origin Card|PIO cards]].\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Demographics of Costa Rica]]\n* [http://www.sircostarica.com/ Costa Rica Real Estate, Cost of Living and Real Estate Law]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Notes ==\n*1. ''The statistics of this page comes from the Wikipedia page in Spanish [[:es:Costa Rica#Demograf.C3.ADa|(Costa Rica) in section demography]].''\n*2.''some sections are partial translations of the Spanish Wikipedia page [[:es:Inmigraci\u00f3n en Costa Rica|(Inmigracion en Costa Rica)]] [https://es.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Inmigraci%C3%B3n_en_Costa_Rica&action=history and its creators].''\n\n{{Ethnic groups in Costa Rica}}\n{{North America in topic|Immigration to}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Immigration To Costa Rica}}\n[[Category:Demographics of Costa Rica]]\n", "name_user": "JalenFolf", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Removing link(s) to \"Europeans\":WP:OLINK. (TW))", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Immigration_to_Costa_Rica"}
{"title_page": "2000 St. Louis Rams season", "text_new": "{{Infobox NFL season\n| team = St. Louis Rams\n| year = 2000\n| record = 10\u20136\n| division_place = 2nd [[NFC West]]\n| coach = [[Mike Martz]]\n| owner = [[Georgia Frontiere]]\n| stadium = [[Trans World Dome]]\n| playoffs = Lost [[2000\u201301 NFL playoffs|Wild Card Playoffs]] ([[2000 New Orleans Saints season|Saints]]) 28\u201331\n| pro bowlers = 5\n<!-- Commented out: |uniform = File:NFCW-Uniform-jersey -STL2000-2007.png -->\n| shortnavlink    = Rams seasons\n}}\n\nThe '''[[2000 NFL season|2000]] [[St. Louis Rams]] season''' was the team's 63rd year with the [[National Football League]] and the sixth season in St. Louis. For the first time in franchise history, the Rams entered the season as the defending Super Bowl champions. The Rams finished the regular-season with a record of 10\u20136 but would go on to lose to the [[New Orleans Saints]] in the Wild Card round of the playoffs. They led the [[National Football League|NFL]] in scoring for a second straight year with 540 points. The Rams became the first team in NFL history to score more than 500 points on offense, while allowing more than 450 points on defense.<ref>Sports Illustrated</ref>\n\nRunning back [[Marshall Faulk]] was named the [[National Football League Most Valuable Player Award|MVP]] of the regular season. It was the second straight time a Rams player was named MVP.\n\nAfter the resignation of [[Dick Vermeil]], who had been the Rams' head coach through St. Louis' [[1999 St. Louis Rams season|1999 championship season]], [[Mike Martz]] took over as head coach, and attempted to defend the Rams' [[Super Bowl XXXIV]] title. The Rams' \"[[Greatest Show on Turf]]\" continued its offensive dominance, scoring 33.7 points per game.\n\nStatistically, [[Football Outsiders]] calculates that the 2000 Rams had the most efficient rushing attack of any single-season NFL team from 1993\u20132010.<ref>[http://www.footballoutsiders.com/dvoa-ratings/2011/final-2010-dvoa-ratings Final 2010 DVOA Ratings]</ref> The 2000 Rams are one of only three teams in NFL history to score 35 points or more nine times in a single season.<ref>[http://pfref.com/tiny/EA42f Pro-Football-Reference.com: In a single season, from 1940 to 2011, in the regular season, requiring Points For >= 35, sorted by most games in season matching criteria.]</ref><ref>The other two are the [[1948 San Francisco 49ers season|1948 49ers]] and the [[2011 Green Bay Packers season|2011 Packers]]</ref> The Rams' offense offset the team's defensive struggles: St. Louis' 471 points allowed in 2000 is the most ever surrendered by an NFL team with a winning record.<ref>[http://pfref.com/tiny/dNYZa Pro-Football-Reference.com: In a single season, from 1940 to 2012, in the Regular Season, team with winning record, sorted by descending Points Allowed.]</ref>\n\nThe season saw the Rams change their logo and add a new color scheme of navy and gold, replacing blue and yellow, donning new uniforms in the process.\n==Offseason==\n\n===NFL Draft===\n{{main article|2000 NFL Draft}}\n{{NFL team draft start\n | year     = 2000\n | teamname = St. Louis Rams\n}}\n{{NFL team draft entry\n | round      = 1\n | pick       = 31\n | player     = [[Trung Canidate]]\n | position   = [[Running back]]\n | college    = [[Arizona Wildcats football|Arizona]]\n | notes      = \n | maderoster = yes\n}}\n{{NFL team draft end\n | probowl = no\n | hof     = no\n}}\n<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/ram/2000_draft.htm |title=2000 St. Louis Rams draftees |work=Pro-Football-Reference.com |accessdate=October 6, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n===Staff===\n{{NFL final staff\n| year = 2000\n| team = St. Louis Rams\n\n| front_office =\n* Chairman \u2013 [[Georgia Frontiere]]\n* Vice Chairman \u2013 [[Stan Kroenke]]\n* President \u2013 John Shaw\n* President of Football Operations \u2013 Jay Zygmunt\n* General Manager \u2013 Charley Armey\n* Senior Vice President of Administration \u2013 Bob 